You need to configure Firebase in two places:

Firebase Console for the mobile app
Firebase Admin credentials for the backend
1. Enable Phone Sign-In
Go to Firebase Console:
https://console.firebase.google.com/

Then:

Open your project: hjamty
In the left menu, go to Authentication
Open the Sign-in method tab
Click Phone
Press Enable
Save
That is what allows Firebase to send real OTP SMS in production.

2. Configure the backend with Firebase Admin
Your backend verifies the Firebase ID token after the user enters the SMS code. For that, the backend needs Firebase Admin credentials.

In Firebase Console:

Go to Project settings
Open the Service accounts tab
Click Generate new private key
Download the JSON file
Inside that JSON, you will find values like:

project_id
client_email
private_key
Your backend already supports these env vars in env.ts:

FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID
FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL
FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY
So in production, set them in your backend environment like this:

FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your_project_id
FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL=your_service_account_email
FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
Important:

keep the \n inside the private key
do not paste raw line breaks unless your platform handles multiline secrets correctly
If you use Railway
In Railway:

Open your backend service
Go to Variables
Add:
FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID
FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL
FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY
Then redeploy.

How to know it works
When the backend starts, if Firebase Admin is configured correctly, it should log something like:

Firebase Admin initialized successfully
If not, your new endpoint /api/auth/verify-firebase-token will fail.

Very important for mobile
For Phone Auth to work on Android/iPhone, you still need app-side Firebase setup too:

Android app registered in Firebase
SHA-1 / SHA-256 added
correct google-services.json
iOS app setup if you test on iPhone
